\section{Institutional Modes}

Kapnet should support multiple real-world institutional forms without redesigning the kernel for each one.

\subsection{Family Mode}

A family can use the node to:

\begin{itemize}
    \item maintain shared memory,
    \item route household or long-horizon tasks,
    \item keep scoped archives,
    \item assign trusted roles,
    \item coordinate small treasury decisions.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Firm Mode}

A firm can use the node to:

\begin{itemize}
    \item distribute cognition across workers and agents,
    \item buy or sell validation,
    \item integrate weakwork or HODL-derived privilege into costs or access,
    \item maintain durable process memory,
    \item route machine work and receipts.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Cooperative Mode}

A cooperative can use the node to:

\begin{itemize}
    \item define membership and roles,
    \item balance contribution and patience-derived rights,
    \item govern internal policy,
    \item allocate validation and archive budgets,
    \item preserve decisions and receipts.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Federation Mode}

A federation can use the node to:

\begin{itemize}
    \item coordinate among multiple DAOs,
    \item shard governance and archival policy,
    \item route cognition between units,
    \item maintain common service providers,
    \item support both public and private fabrics.
\end{itemize}

