\section{Node Capability Implications}

If this utility profile is correct, then node capability descriptors must expose more than generic protocol support.

A node or provider should be able to advertise whether it supports:

\begin{itemize}
    \item DAO registry and membership,
    \item DAO creation and governance support,
    \item weakwork claim and routing services,
    \item HODL / ATY accounting and exposure services,
    \item cognition routing and task coordination,
    \item archive and validation,
    \item public or private fabrics,
    \item Nostr-aware or Nostr-bridged operation,
    \item market intermediation between privilege surfaces.
\end{itemize}

This is the direct bridge from the protocol layer to the product layer.

\section{Runtime Expectations}

A node implementing this profile should make the following runtime flows natural.

\subsection{Join DAO Flow}

\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
    \item Discover DAO scope.
    \item Fetch rules and provider surfaces.
    \item Join as a member or role-holder.
    \item Begin receiving member-addressed and feed content.
    \item Participate in governance or work routing.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Make DAO Flow}

\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
    \item Create new scope.
    \item Bind rules, validation defaults, and archive defaults.
    \item Select fabrics and providers.
    \item Publish capability and policy surfaces.
    \item Begin accepting members and routing cognition.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Sell Weakwork Flow}

\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
    \item Submit or expose weakwork claim.
    \item Observe award and decay state.
    \item Route awarded weakwork into markets.
    \item Exchange for access, sponsorship, or payment.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Sell HODL-Derived Privilege Flow}

\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
    \item Inspect HODL-derived privilege.
    \item Offer exposure or leasing under relevant policy.
    \item Bind rights to DAO or provider surfaces.
    \item Receive compensation or reciprocal access.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Distribute Cognition Flow}

\begin{enumerate}[label=\arabic*.]
    \item Define tasks or proposals.
    \item Route to bounded humans or agents.
    \item Receive receipts.
    \item Request validation or risk coverage.
    \item Archive decisions and outputs.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Recommended Implementation Order}

The utility profile suggests a pragmatic implementation order.

\subsection{Priority 1: DAO Membership and Foundry}

The first node utility should let users:

\begin{itemize}
    \item discover and join DAOs,
    \item create and configure DAOs,
    \item receive member-addressed submissions,
    \item browse scoped feeds.
\end{itemize}

This gives immediate organizational utility.

\subsection{Priority 2: Weakwork Wallet}

The next utility should let small hashers:

\begin{itemize}
    \item submit weakwork claims,
    \item track decay,
    \item route work privilege into markets.
\end{itemize}

This gives immediate producer-side economic utility.

\subsection{Priority 3: HODL / ATY Wallet}

The next utility should let savers:

\begin{itemize}
    \item inspect HODL-derived privilege,
    \item view and route patience-derived rights,
    \item participate in long-horizon DAO and provider economics.
\end{itemize}

This gives immediate saver-side economic utility.

\subsection{Priority 4: Cognition Router}

The next utility should let organizations:

\begin{itemize}
    \item distribute tasks,
    \item coordinate humans and agents,
    \item preserve memory,
    \item attach validation and settlement surfaces.
\end{itemize}

This gives the broader adoptive-organization utility.

\section{Strongest Concise Formulation}

The full utility story can be compressed into one line:

\begin{quote}
A Kapnet node should let anyone join and found DAOs, monetize spare hashpower as weakwork, monetize patient saving as HODL-derived privilege, and distribute cognition across families, firms, federations, and agent systems.
\end{quote}

A slightly more compressed version is:

\begin{quote}
Kapnet node utility is institutional membership, institutional creation, hashpower monetization, patience monetization, and cognition distribution.
\end{quote}

\section{Conclusion}

This utility profile gives Kapnet a concrete node-facing identity. The node is not merely a consensus participant or a relay endpoint. It is a machine that lets operators convert three kinds of surplus into agency:

\begin{itemize}
    \item hashpower into weakwork,
    \item patience into HODL-derived privilege,
    \item cognition into coordinated organizational action.
\end{itemize}

That is the correct practical framing for the system. It binds the protocol to real operator incentives, real organizational forms, and real service markets. It also gives a clear implementation horizon: the node should first be able to join and make DAOs, expose weakwork and HODL utility, and route cognition for adoptive organizations. If those things are real, the rest of the system has a living center.

